comments.text: James Van Der Beek reminds me of that movie “We Live In Time” with Florence Pugh and Andrew Garfield. You fall in love, you have a family together, then you get cancer. I wish cancer didn’t exist in our lives but if you are made aware of your condition you can at least make the most of your life with the people you love most. You can either give up or cherish your remaining years. I hate it for he and his family but at least they got to prepare for this and hopefully they were able to live their life to the fullest with what time they had left. Just another reminder to tell the ones you love most “I love you” on a daily basis. You never know what will come your way and you don’t want to be wishing for more time with someone. Prayers for that family and all of their friends. Rest in peace 🙏

comments.text:
I think that set designers should get residuals as well. There is no reason why companies should be making millions and millions of dollars off rerun TV shows and the actors themselves not making any money from it. In that sense, it’s just the rich getting richer. The actors need to be able to catch up to those rich people as well, just like the lower class needs to be able to catch up to the middle class. It’s the same thing — just a different bracket.

There’s no reason why The Parkers is making ad executives and company managers millions of dollars today — today and yesterday — and Mo’Nique isn’t making one cent from that show because she didn’t know how to negotiate her contract properly at the time.

Honestly, I think actors need to be able to go to court and sue for back residuals, or at least secure residuals moving forward, because this just isn’t right. I’m surprised there hasn’t already been more legal action over unpaid or unfair residual agreements. It feels like there should be a precedent for that.
